Describe a park or a garden in your city
- How often you go there
- Where it is
- Who you often go there with
- What it is like
- Explain why you like to visit it

I’m going to talk about Tao Dan Park, which is one of my favorite green spaces in the city.

It’s located in District 1, right in the city center, although it’s a bit far from my home. It usually takes me around 20 minutes to get there by motorbike, depending on traffic. I don’t go there very often, maybe once or twice a month, usually when I have some free time. Sometimes I go with friends, but I also enjoy visiting it alone.

I first visited this park about two years ago during a university club outing, and I remember being really impressed by how peaceful it was compared to the busy streets outside. Since then, I’ve come back quite a few times. Sometimes I just find a quiet bench, put on my headphones, and listen to music while watching people walk by.

The park itself feels like a small oasis in the middle of the city. There are lots of tall trees, shaded paths, and well-maintained gardens. In the mornings, people usually go there to exercise, and in the afternoons, families bring their kids to play. One of my favorite spots is the flower garden, especially during Tet, when it’s full of colorful decorations—it’s actually one of the most beautiful times to visit.

What I really like about this place is the atmosphere. Whenever I feel stressed or tired, going there helps me relax and clear my mind. I also enjoy just sitting there and doing nothing for a while, which is something I don’t usually get to do in my daily routine. That’s why it has become one of my go-to places whenever I need a break.
